{
  "doc_id": "18655",
  "text": "Managing water scarcity has emerged as a growing challenge globally, particularly for rural livelihoods dependent on rainfed agriculture (United Nations 2015; [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . In the face of increasing demand from urbanisation, cultivation of new water-demanding crops, agricultural intensification, misuse and over extraction, population pressures, and the impacts of climate variability and change, water scarcity remains a crucial limiting factor driving farmer vulnerability. The Indian state of Rajasthan is an illustrative example of these interrelated challenges. Rajasthan has the country's largest arid and semi-arid area and faces acute water scarcity due to erratic monsoonal rainfall as well as critically overexploited groundwater resources.",
